Plotting Trends for Total, Private & Public Construction Spending¶

Initial Takeaways¶
  • Both Private and Public construction trends show defined seasonality
  • While Public construction shows more linearity, neither Public nor Private construction follow a consistent trend over time
  • Private construction is likely showing us a combination of both seasonality and cyclicality BUT we don't see repeated cycles in this data

Public Construction - Decomposition¶

  • Step 1: plot the Moving Average of our time series where our window is greater than 12 months (if less than our moving average won't smooth out)
  • Step 2: determine average Seasonality across monthly increments
  • Step 3: combine Moving Average and Seasonality to form a composite model
In [66]:
df['MovAvg'] = np.NaN
df['sqErr'] = np.NaN

df.index = pd.DatetimeIndex(freq='m',data=pd.date_range(freq='m',start=pd.Timestamp(year=2002,month=1,day=31),periods=len(df.Public)))

window = 36  # (months)
window = window - window % 2

for i in range(int(window/2),df.shape[0]-int(window/2)):
    df.loc[df.index[i],'MovAvg'] = (0.5*df.iloc[i - int(window/2)]['Public'] + df.iloc[i - int(window/2)+1:i + int(window/2)]['Public'].sum() + 0.5*df.iloc[i + int(window/2)]['Public'])/float(window)

df['sqErr'] = (df['Public'] - df['MovAvg'])**2
df.dropna(how='any',inplace=True)  # drop any rows that we cannot compute a moving average for 

fig,ax = plt.subplots()
fig.suptitle('Construction Spending Trends', fontsize = 14)
fig.set_size_inches(16,6)
ax.plot(df['MovAvg'],label='Moving Avg', color = 'limegreen')
ax.plot(df['Public'],label='Actual', color = 'black')
ax.set_xlabel('Month')
ax.set_ylabel('Construction Spending')
ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)

Plotting Residuals Post-Moving Average¶

Takeaways:¶
  • Seasonality pattern looks to explain most of the remaining residuals
  • In some cases the Seasonality looks to be more pronounced (later years show more variance and earlier years)
In [67]:
df['R1'] = df['Public'] - df['MovAvg']   # 1st remainder
df['R1Error'] = abs((df['Public'] - df['R1'])/df['Public'])

Running Autocorrelation to Determine Seasonality Increments¶

Takeaways:¶
  • Our residuals show the strongest autocorrelation at lags 11-13
  • This confirms our initial thought on a yearly seasonality
In [68]:
auto_corr = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Lag_Value', 'AutoCorr']) 

for i in range(1,25):   # int(len(df.index)/2)
    auto_corr.loc[i,'Lag_Value'] = i
    auto_corr.loc[i,'AutoCorr'] = df.Public.autocorr(lag = i)

color_cond = ['firebrick' if ac >= 0.9 else ('orange' if ac > 0.75 else 'lightgrey') for ac in auto_corr['AutoCorr']]
    
fig,ax = plt.subplots()
fig.suptitle('AutoCorrelation Strength by Lag', fontsize = 14)
fig.set_size_inches(16,6)
plt.bar(auto_corr.Lag_Value,auto_corr.AutoCorr, color = color_cond)
ax.set_xticks(auto_corr.Lag_Value[::1])
ax.set_xticklabels(auto_corr.Lag_Value[::1])

Calculating Average Deviations Based on Month from our Residuals Post-Moving Average¶

In [69]:
dfMonth = pd.DataFrame()  # empty dataframe
cycleLen = 12
for i in range(int(len(df.index)/cycleLen)):
    newData = pd.DataFrame({i:df['R1'].iloc[i*cycleLen:(i+1)*cycleLen]})  
    newData.index = range(0,len(newData))
    dfMonth = pd.concat([dfMonth,newData],axis=1)

avg = []
for i in range(len(dfMonth.index)):    
    avg.append(dfMonth.iloc[i].mean())

dfMonth = pd.concat([dfMonth,pd.DataFrame({'avg':avg})], axis=1)
    
    
fig,ax = plt.subplots()
for col in dfMonth.columns.values:  # this is crafty AF
    if col == 'avg':
        ax.plot(dfMonth[col], c = 'firebrick')
    else:
        ax.plot(dfMonth[col], c = 'lightgrey')
display()

Adding in Seasonality to our Model from the Residual-Based Averages¶

In [70]:
df.reset_index(inplace = True)

df['S'] = np.NaN    # seasonal effect in each quarter, we will subtract this from R1
df['R2'] = np.NaN    # will serve as remainder after accounting for seasonality (the noise)
df['Composite'] = np.NaN   # total model (level + Trend + Seasonal)
df['errorPerc'] = np.NaN   # % of error from our noise
S = dfMonth['avg'].tolist()
for i in df.index:
    df.loc[i,'S'] = S[i%cycleLen]   
    df.loc[i,'R2'] = df.loc[i,'R1'] - df.loc[i,'S']
    df.loc[i,'Composite'] = df.loc[i,'MovAvg'] + df.loc[i,'S']
    df.loc[i,'errorPerc'] = 100*df.loc[i,'R2'] / df.loc[i,'Public']
df.style.format({
    'Public': '{:,.0f}'.format,
    'MovAvg': '{:,.0f}'.format,
    'sqErr': '{:,.0f}'.format,
    'R1': '{:,.0f}'.format,
    'S': '{:,.0f}'.format,
    'R2': '{:,.0f}'.format,
    'Composite':'{:,.0f}'.format,
    'errorPerc': '{:.2f}%'.format    # two decimal places with %
})

Plotting The Revised Model With Both Trend (Moving Average) and Seasonality Accounted For¶

Overall, this model fits well with the actual trend for Public construction. The remaining error in the model is driven by differences in variance of the seasonal fluctuations over time within the trend. Because we used the average seasonality in our adjusted model, we overshoot the seasonality in earlier years and undershoot it in later years.

Creating the Moving Average and Plotting it for Private Construction¶

In [75]:
priv_df['MovAvg'] = np.NaN
priv_df['sqErr'] = np.NaN

priv_df.index = pd.DatetimeIndex(freq='m',data=pd.date_range(freq='m',start=pd.Timestamp(year=2002,month=1,day=31),periods=len(priv_df.Private)))

window = 12  # (months)
window = window - window % 2

for i in range(int(window/2),priv_df.shape[0]-int(window/2)):
    priv_df.loc[priv_df.index[i],'MovAvg'] = (0.5*priv_df.iloc[i - int(window/2)]['Private'] + priv_df.iloc[i - int(window/2)+1:i + int(window/2)]['Private'].sum() + 0.5*priv_df.iloc[i + int(window/2)]['Private'])/float(window)

priv_df['sqErr'] = (priv_df['Private'] - priv_df['MovAvg'])**2
priv_df.dropna(how='any',inplace=True)  # drop any rows that we cannot compute a moving average for 

fig,ax = plt.subplots()
fig.set_size_inches(16,6)
ax.plot(priv_df['MovAvg'],label='Moving Avg', color = 'limegreen')
ax.plot(priv_df['Private'],label='Actual', color = 'black')
ax.set_xlabel('Month')
ax.set_ylabel('Construction')
ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)

priv_dfMonth = pd.DataFrame()  # empty dataframe
cycleLen = 12
for i in range(int(len(priv_df.index)/cycleLen)):
    newData = pd.DataFrame({i:priv_df['R1'].iloc[i*cycleLen:(i+1)*cycleLen]})  
    newData.index = range(0,len(newData))
    priv_dfMonth = pd.concat([priv_dfMonth,newData],axis=1)

avg = []
for i in range(len(priv_dfMonth.index)):    
    avg.append(priv_dfMonth.iloc[i].mean())

priv_dfMonth = pd.concat([priv_dfMonth, pd.DataFrame({'avg':avg})], axis=1)
    
    
fig,ax = plt.subplots()
for col in priv_dfMonth.columns.values:  # this is crafty AF

Using Avg Seasonal Adjustments and Embedding Them Into Our Refined Model¶

In [79]:
priv_df.reset_index(inplace = True)

priv_df['S'] = np.NaN    # seasonal effect in each quarter, we will subtract this from R1
priv_df['R2'] = np.NaN    # will serve as remainder after accounting for seasonality (the noise)
priv_df['Composite'] = np.NaN   # total model (level + Trend + Seasonal)
priv_df['errorPerc'] = np.NaN   # % of error from our noise
S = priv_dfMonth['avg'].tolist()
for i in priv_df.index:
    priv_df.loc[i,'S'] = S[i%cycleLen]   
    priv_df.loc[i,'R2'] = priv_df.loc[i,'R1'] - priv_df.loc[i,'S']
    priv_df.loc[i,'Composite'] = priv_df.loc[i,'MovAvg'] + priv_df.loc[i,'S']
    priv_df.loc[i,'errorPerc'] = 100 * priv_df.loc[i,'R2'] / priv_df.loc[i,'Public']
priv_df.style.format({
    'Public': '{:,.0f}'.format,
    'MovAvg': '{:,.0f}'.format,
    'sqErr': '{:,.0f}'.format,
    'R1': '{:,.0f}'.format,
    'S': '{:,.0f}'.format,
    'R2': '{:,.0f}'.format,
    'Composite':'{:,.0f}'.format,
    'errorPerc': '{:.2f}%'.format    # two decimal places with %
})

Plotting Final Model with the Fitted Values¶

In [80]:
x = priv_df['Date']

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
fig.suptitle('Fitted Model vs. Actual Data: Private Construction', fontsize = 14)
fig.set_size_inches(16,6)
ax.plot(x, priv_df['Private'],c='black', label = 'Actual')
ax.plot(x, priv_df['Composite'],c='fuchsia', label = 'Model', linestyle = 'dashed')   # 'Composite' serves as our model

ax.set_xticks(x[::4])
ax.set_xticklabels(x[::4])
ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
ax.set_xlabel('Month', fontsize = 14)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
ax.set_ylabel('Private Construction', fontsize = 14)
ax.legend(loc = 2, fontsize = 14)
plt.show()

Histogram of Final Residuals¶

avg_resid = priv_df['R2'].mean()

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.hist(x = priv_df['R2'], bins = 15, facecolor='navy', alpha=0.5)
# 'hist' signals a histogram

fig.suptitle('Private Construction Residual Histogram', fontsize = 14)
fig.set_size_inches(7,5)
ax.axvline(x=avg_resid,linewidth=2,color='red',linestyle='-', label = 'Average')

ax.xaxis.set_label_text('Residuals from Final Model')
ax.xaxis.set_tick_params(which = 'both', top = False, bottom = True, labelbottom = True)  # Turn top x axis tick marks off 
ax.yaxis.set_label_text('Frequency of Residuals')
ax.yaxis.set_tick_params(which = 'both', right = False, left = True, labelleft = True)   # Turn right y axis tick marks off
ax.legend()
plt.show()
